/**
 * \page record_replay_page Recording and Replaying Coupling Data

\author Nils-Arne Dreier (DKRZ)

This page explains how to use the record and replay tools to capture and later replay coupling data, for example, in a continuous integration (CI) environment.

Both tools rely on <a href="https://uxarray.readthedocs.io/en/latest/">UXarray</a> to load and store grids and data, which means they can accept any grid format supported by `uxarray.open_grid`. To view available options and parameters, run each tool with the `--help` flag.

In addition to `UXarray` and YAC’s Python bindings, the following Python packages are required and must be installed in your environment:
- `numpy`
- `isodate`

\section record_ICON Recording Data

To record data sent by the ocean component to the atmosphere during a simulation, add `yac_record.py` as an additional process in your run script:

\code{.sh}
python yac_record.py ${ocean_grid} ocean_record.nc \
  sea_surface_temperature \
  eastward_sea_water_velocity \
  northward_sea_water_velocity \
  ocean_sea_ice_bundle \
  --log-level INFO --coupling-config record_coupling.yaml
\endcode

The `record_coupling.yaml` file defines the coupling configuration for the record component:

\code{.yaml}
calendar: proleptic-gregorian
timestep_unit: ISO_format
coupling:
  - source:
      component: ocean
      grid: icon_ocean_grid
    target:
      component: record
      grid: record_grid
    field:
      - sea_surface_temperature
      - eastward_sea_water_velocity
      - northward_sea_water_velocity
      - ocean_sea_ice_bundle
    coupling_period: PT30M
    src_lag: 1
    tgt_lag: 1
    interpolation:
      - nnn
\endcode

When you run this setup, it will create an `ocean_record.nc` file containing the recorded data. You can then analyze or visualize the data using `UXarray` in a Jupyter notebook.

\section replay_ICON Replaying Data

To replace the ocean component with recorded data in an existing ICON run script, follow these steps:
- **Disable the ocean component:** For example, comment out the line assigning the ocean namelist (e.g., `#namelist_list[1]="$oce_namelist"`). ICON will no longer launch ocean processes.
- **Comment out all couplings from the atmosphere to the ocean** in your `coupling.yaml` configuration, since the replay tool does not provide the required fields to receive these data. Alternatively, you can set `missing_definition_is_fatal: false`.
- **Add a process running the replay tool** with the following command:

\code{.sh}
python yac_replay.py ${ocean_grid} ocean_record.nc --compname ocean --gridname icon_ocean_grid --cell-mask 'cell_sea_land_mask < 0' --log-level INFO
\endcode

Here, the component name and grid name for the replay tool are set to `ocean` and `icon_ocean_grid` so that the existing coupling definitions in the run script can be reused. The grid mask is also specified, as this is required for compatibility with ICON-ocean and ensures identical results.

*/
